00:43:20,191 --> 00:43:26,231
Rym: Even though I like the TV show more than the movies... Zelda 2 is canonically an explicit sequel of Zelda 1.

641
00:43:26,231 --> 00:43:26,526
Rym: But anyway...

642
00:43:26,610 --> 00:43:37,210
Scott: The existence of these movies, the fact that they're there, actually, somehow, makes the TV show better.

643
00:43:37,630 --> 00:43:37,762
Rym: Yes!

644
00:43:38,290 --> 00:43:42,150
Scott: It's like, the TV show is better because the movie's here.

645
00:43:42,230 --> 00:43:55,530
Scott: It's the opposite of what nerds complain about, which obviously isn't true, is that, oh, you ruined the thing I like by making a new thing, which can't possibly happen because you could just pretend the new thing isn't there.

646
00:43:55,550 --> 00:43:56,534
Rym: It's almost put me into a loop.

647
00:43:56,715 --> 00:44:00,330
Rym: Watching these movies, I really want to go back and watch the entire show again.

648
00:44:00,671 --> 00:44:06,030
Rym: But if I watch the entire show again, I feel like I'm going to think, oh, now I want to watch the movies again.

649
00:44:08,231 --> 00:44:16,150
Scott: It's like, if these movies were, say, garbage, completely awful, the TV show would still be as good as it was on its own.

650
00:44:16,350 --> 00:44:20,950
Rym: And we could just ignore the movies, like we do for those other Indiana Jones movies.

651
00:44:21,270 --> 00:44:26,690
Scott: That original artwork cannot be harmed, but it's not easy to elevate it either.

652
00:44:27,710 --> 00:44:46,930
Scott: The movies, even if you don't think they're good, even if you don't like them, or don't like them as much as the TV show, I like them just not as much as the TV show, they somehow have the power to, if you have seen them, the original TV show now means more.

653
00:44:47,250 --> 00:44:52,850
Scott: It has become elevated in a way because there was a rebuild that happened later.

654
00:44:52,970 --> 00:44:54,435
Rym: And I'd say it's from two angles.

655
00:44:54,595 --> 00:44:59,530
Rym: On one hand, it reinforces the underlying themes of the original show.

656
00:44:59,590 --> 00:45:06,450
Rym: So you watch the original show again, and you can compare all these different paths and really internalize the meta message.

657
00:45:06,990 --> 00:45:17,670
Rym: But also, the movie explores many of the worldbuilding and science fiction aspects of the show that were footnotes in the show and vice versa.

658
00:45:17,870 --> 00:45:20,357
Rym: I'll give an example that's not super spoiler-ly.

659
00:45:20,517 --> 00:45:28,201
Rym: In the show, there's a moment where you find out there's a nerve base in the US, and there's an accident there, and it just disappears.

660
00:45:28,622 --> 00:45:29,205
Rym: It blows up.

661
00:45:29,326 --> 00:45:30,350
Rym: There's a big disaster.

662
00:45:31,972 --> 00:45:32,717
Scott: It's like a footnote.

663
00:45:32,758 --> 00:45:34,410
Scott: Isn't that in the lava episode, I want to say?

664
00:45:34,450 --> 00:45:35,052
Rym: I think so.

665
00:45:35,093 --> 00:45:36,920
Rym: I forget exactly, but I think you're right.

666
00:45:37,201 --> 00:45:39,429
Rym: So that just happens, and characters react to it.

667
00:45:39,830 --> 00:45:43,619
Rym: But you don't get an episode where they go and investigate it.

668
00:45:43,899 --> 00:45:48,490
Rym: In the movies, that happens, and they go fucking deal with it.

669
00:45:50,251 --> 00:45:56,741
Scott: Yeah, because the original TV show has these hints that early in the TV show, they deliver AV unit 3.

670
00:45:56,741 --> 00:45:57,423
Scott: It's delivered.

671
00:46:02,814 --> 00:46:03,518
Rym: From Europe.

672
00:46:04,302 --> 00:46:05,930
Rym: Well, O2 from Europe.

673
00:46:06,730 --> 00:46:08,041
Rym: And then 3.

674
00:46:08,041 --> 00:46:09,631
Scott: Anyway, it's unit 2.

675
00:46:09,631 --> 00:46:11,050
Rym: It's unit 2, but it's the third one.

676
00:46:12,311 --> 00:46:13,936
Scott: But yeah, it gets delivered.

677
00:46:14,258 --> 00:46:17,570
Scott: But they never show you what the hell is... Kaji comes from somewhere else.

678
00:46:21,756 --> 00:46:25,330
Scott: In the end of Evangelion, spoilers, all those white ones show up.

679
00:46:26,451 --> 00:46:27,915
Scott: It's like, where did they come from?

680
00:46:27,935 --> 00:46:34,230
Scott: The movies actually go and show you what's going on around other parts of the world.

681
00:46:34,390 --> 00:46:36,978
Rym: You see Kaji doing his spy shit.

682
00:46:37,018 --> 00:46:40,710
Rym: You see the place where the things come from.

683
00:46:41,111 --> 00:46:45,068
Rym: I'm trying not to talk about that, but the place where the things come from.

684
00:46:46,170 --> 00:46:54,910
Scott: There's a lot of blanks that got filled in, and it's not new information, because all that stuff was in the TV show.

685
00:46:54,930 --> 00:46:58,510
Rym: And that stuff was not material to the message or even the plot.

686
00:46:59,650 --> 00:47:08,510
Scott: Right, but because it matters for the plot of these movies, which is a different plot, they're now showing you all those things this time, before you didn't see them.

687
00:47:09,171 --> 00:47:15,750
Rym: So you get to flesh out the physical events from the show and the movie, and you also get to flesh out the themes.

688
00:47:16,390 --> 00:47:22,813
Rym: But the moments that gave me the chills watching the movies were... There are iconic scenes in the show.

689
00:47:22,913 --> 00:47:33,550
Rym: The one I'm thinking of very specifically is when the skull-faced alien gets near terminal dogma and is staring Masato in the face.

690
00:47:34,070 --> 00:47:39,049
Rym: That scene in the show is one of the most haunting scenes in the entire show to me.

691
00:47:39,690 --> 00:47:52,690
Rym: And that exact same scene, with very different events leading up to it and very different events happening after it, but the two worlds almost converge into that scene being identical in the second movie.

692
00:47:53,810 --> 00:48:03,710
Rym: And the fact that the two stories I've seen intersected so perfectly and then diverge again at that moment, that stuck with me.

693
00:48:04,390 --> 00:48:14,530
Rym: And that is how the whole of these two sets of tellings of the story, the episodes versus the movies, are greater than the sum of their parts.

694
00:48:15,593 --> 00:48:29,250
Scott: So the second movie, unlike the first movie, while it's pretty much all stuff that did not happen in the TV show, it still is sort of like almost slightly altered events from the TV show.

695
00:48:30,112 --> 00:48:36,650
Scott: There are things that happen in the TV show that kind of happen in the second movie differently, mixed up a little bit.

696
00:48:37,591 --> 00:48:39,902
Rym: Some things from later in the show happen then.

697
00:48:40,264 --> 00:48:41,370
Rym: Brand new things happen.

698
00:48:41,891 --> 00:48:51,949
Rym: But the atmosphere is different, because the thing about these movies that's so striking is that each movie has a radically different vibe and feeling and mood.

699
00:48:53,010 --> 00:49:02,490
Rym: The second movie really focuses on the scale of what humanity has built, but also the fact that Earth is teeming with life.

700
00:49:03,312 --> 00:49:10,950
Rym: This positive optimism of humans were trying to save the world, and all the atmospheric scenes, it's not the cicadas.

701
00:49:11,210 --> 00:49:15,589
Scott: That's what comes from the old robot shows that Evangelion is one of.

702
00:49:16,570 --> 00:49:28,389
Rym: But instead of all the cicadas and the emptiness that is so pervasive in the original show, you see a world filled with people, teeming with life, going about their days, trying to survive and rebuild.

703
00:49:29,553 --> 00:49:34,950
Rym: And I think that's really epitomized by the scene where Kaji takes them on the field trip with the ocean stuff.

704
00:49:35,750 --> 00:49:45,370
Rym: And then it all kind of goes to shit, and the third movie is more like the empty times, coupled with things that are very hard to talk about without spoiling huge things.

705
00:49:45,950 --> 00:49:50,730
Scott: So the third movie basically has no overlap with the original TV show whatsoever.

706
00:49:51,431 --> 00:50:00,929
Scott: It's like the first movie, you're on the TV side, the second movie is sort of like this border space, and the third movie is completely in a new thing.

707
00:50:01,530 --> 00:50:06,698
Rym: The second movie is off the rails, but you're still in the same universe.

708
00:50:06,718 --> 00:50:14,789
Rym: You're on a train and the scenery is very different, but you're still like, "Alright, I see how this track came from the track I was

709
00:50:14,949 --> 00:50:15,009
Rym: on.".

710
00:50:15,490 --> 00:50:20,770
Rym: And then after that, it's just like the train has fallen off a cliff and is in space somehow.

711
00:50:21,710 --> 00:50:30,690
Scott: Right, and so there's four movies, and somehow, even though these are four anime movies, you know they're going to be four of them, they're in a series.

712
00:50:31,390 --> 00:50:38,950
Scott: Usually, when you are going to make an anime series, even Evangelion, you save your terrible secret of space for the last few episodes.

713
00:50:39,351 --> 00:50:46,730
Rym: No, the terrible secret of space goes beyond what you would have possibly ever expected before the end of the second movie.

714
00:50:47,570 --> 00:50:48,151
Scott: Right.

715
00:50:48,332 --> 00:50:55,390
Scott: Here, it's like each individual movie goes terrible secret of space at the end, even though the first one only does a little bit.

716
00:50:57,152 --> 00:51:02,590
Scott: And it's like, how was the end of the third movie not the end of the whole thing?

717
00:51:03,791 --> 00:51:12,970
Rym: I mean, the end of the second movie, but for something that happens in the final seconds of it, could have been the end of Evangelion.

718
00:51:13,890 --> 00:51:14,709
Scott: Yeah, it could have just been.

719
00:51:14,930 --> 00:51:19,061
Rym: And I say that literally as in, remember the movie end of Evangelion?

720
00:51:19,101 --> 00:51:22,730
Rym: Like, yup, sure, that is literally the end, game over.

721
00:51:23,610 --> 00:51:30,710
Scott: Yeah, it's like the events that happen in each of the movies are so climactic, they could be, you know, it's just like four ends.

722
00:51:31,811 --> 00:51:38,230
Scott: It's like the power, you know, usually animes save up their power for the end and then release the full blast.

723
00:51:38,571 --> 00:51:44,103
Rym: This is more like Promare, the movie, where it just keeps escalating and escalating and escalating.

724
00:51:44,344 --> 00:51:46,910
Rym: It's like a song that just keeps swelling and no point dies down.

725
00:51:47,010 --> 00:51:53,069
